B-sort: deterministic contact-resolution order for kinematic move_and_slide
============================================================================
Target: godot-rapier-physics v0.8.36 (rapier 0.33.0 / parry 0.28.0),
        single-enhanced-determinism flavor.
File:   src/spaces/rapier_space_body_helper.rs, fn rapier_intersect_aabb.

WHY: the broad phase yields colliders in BVH-traversal order, which is
regenerated differently after import_state (godot-rapier #534). The kinematic
motion recovery (recover_motion_from_contacts — order-dependent accumulation,
~L105) and the cast tie-break (cast_motion — strict-< first-wins, ~L894) both
consume this order, so a shuffled order flips the resolved contact on replay.
Sorting the result set by the stable Godot collider identity (UserData{part1,
part2}, set at collider creation, independent of Rapier handle order) makes the
iteration order identical in record and replay. Pure reordering of an existing
result set — no collision math changed. Only the 3 motion-path callers
(body_motion_recover, cast_motion, body_motion_collide) reach this helper.

--- a/src/spaces/rapier_space_body_helper.rs
+++ b/src/spaces/rapier_space_body_helper.rs
@@ rapier_intersect_aabb (tail) @@
-        physics_engine.intersect_aabb(
+        let count = physics_engine.intersect_aabb(
             self.get_state().get_id(),
             vector_to_rapier(rect_begin),
             vector_to_rapier(rect_end),
             collide_with_bodies,
             collide_with_areas,
             results,
             max_results,
             &handle_excluded_info,
             physics_collision_objects,
             physics_ids,
             self,
-        ) as i32
+        ) as i32;
+        // B-SORT (determinism): broad-phase yields colliders in BVH-traversal order, which is
+        // regenerated differently after import_state (#534); the motion recovery + cast tie-break
+        // are order-dependent. Sort by the stable Godot collider identity so record == replay.
+        if count > 1 {
+            results[0..count as usize].sort_by_key(|r| (r.user_data.part1, r.user_data.part2));
+        }
+        count
     }
